         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">21/6/95 ¶  ¶ Allow me, dear Prof. Robinson, to ask you for information regarding the systematic names of some N. American species of Fraxinus. C. Koch in his Dendrology ¶  gives F. nigra of Marsh as t...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">95.06.21a</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To Benjamin Robinson</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">Library of the Gray Herbarium, Harvard University, Cambridge, Massachusetts.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">21/6/95</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Allow me, dear Prof. Robinson, to ask you for information regarding the systematic names of some N. American species of Fraxinus. C. Koch in his Dendrology<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>K. Koch (1869-72), vol. 2, p. 257.</p>
               </note> gives F. nigra of Marsh as the eldest name for F. sambucifolia; but Hooker &amp; Jackson in the Kew Index admit a still older F. nigra, that of Bosc.<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>B. </seg>Jackson (1895), vol. 1, p. 977 (issued 1893).</p>
               </note> What is the latter? Unfortunately H. &amp; J. left in most cases the year of publication out, so that any one, who has not a very large library of phytographic works is left often helpless. This and the not always strict adherence to priority lessens much the value of this otherwise so important work. Two <name key="Fraxinus%20viridis">Fraxinus viridis</name> are also admitted, one from Bosc, the other from Michaux. How should these 2 stand?</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Prof Asa Gray wrote once an article on the exact spelling of Gauthier's name.<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Article not identified from the index to Gray's publications (Watson &amp; Goodale (1888)).</p>
               </note> I mislaid the article. Could you kindly write the exact name down for me.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I am greatly beholden to you and Prof Goodale, for sending to the Smithsonian Institute such a valuable and extensive lot of dried plants.<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="color: #000fff; ">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     </seg>The Smithsonian Institution often served as a forwarding agent for scientific materials being sent from US institutions to other countries.</p>
               </note> It may be some time, ere it arrives, but when it comes I will at once announce the receipt. It will be a gem in the Herbarium here. Pray remember me to the gemial<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>genial?</p>
               </note> Dr Goodale most kindly</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Always regardfully your</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd von Mueller</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Do you think that it would best<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <seg style="">be </seg>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">omitted before best</seg>
                     <seg style="">?</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> to change the word ovary in phytography to ovulary? Ought the calyx-lobes of <name key="Orchideae">Orchideae</name> be called still sepals? If so, we might as well call the lobes of the calyx (say) of a <name key="Lobelia">Lobelia</name> also sepals. When a wrong expression has long been used, we are apt to continue it, remaining unconscious of the incorrectness.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Let me hope that the ferntrees have arrived uninjured.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Fraxinus%20nigra">Fraxinus nigra</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Fraxinus%20sambucifolia">Fraxinus sambucifolia</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Fraxinus%20viridis">Fraxinus viridis</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Lobelia">Lobelia</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Orchideae">Orchideae</name>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
